Here's the xUnit equivalent:

**Per-test setup/teardown** → constructor + `IDisposable`
**One-time setup/teardown** → `IClassFixture<T>` with a fixture class

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();           // SetUp
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();          // TearDown
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | fixture's `Dispose` |
| `[SetUp]` | test class constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose` on test class |
| `[TestFixture]` | *(removed — convention-based)* |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

xUnit creates a **new instance** of the test class per test, so the constructor/`Dispose` pair naturally replaces per-test setup/teardown. The fixture is shared across all tests in the class via dependency injection.
